A month ago I would have completely agreed with David, and I hope that I 
change my mind, but right now, I'm thinking Hillary is a no go. I like 
Hillary Clinton. I think she is qualified, and I think that if she held 
Bernies positions, she might actually be better at implementing them. I 
think Hillary has been treated unfairly by much of the left in at least one 
case. I don't hold her history of corporatism against her. 

When Bill Clinton ran in the 1992 presidential election, the country had 
had a Democrat in the White House for only 4 of the previous 24 years. The 
4 years were Jimmy Carter, and while his reputation somewhat improved in 
later years he was considered an abject failure by everyone. The 
Republicans, especially after Ronald Reagan had learned how to far out fund 
raise the Democrats. Additionally, unions who had made up a big part of the 
Democratic base were shrinking (Reagan again). Due to the way American 
politics in the modern age had become almost exclusively about money, we 
were getting creamed. Bill Clinton hired a Republican strategist, figured 
out how to fundraise with corporations, and won the nominations. No one 
after the '92 election had any issue with the Clinton camp raising money 
from corporations. Bill, Hillary (who was always considered an unofficial 
part of the administration, part of a "two for one deal"), and Al Gore were 
heroes for saving the country from another 4 years of George Herbert Walker 
Bush. Knowing what we know now, we almost certainly would have had another 
invasion of Iraq if Bush had been reelected. They deserved to be considered 
heroes. 

Bill, Hillary, and the administration did a lot of great things. When we 
judge the don't ask, don't tell policy by today's standards, it's 
weaksauce, but in the nineties, it was as progressive as progressive would 
get. Clinton was economically conservative, but at the time, this was 
almost universally considered to be the correct position. Reagan had set 
the hook on right-wing economics, and the US electorate had swallowed it to 
the sinker. We had a tech bubble driving economic prosperity, and it seemed 
like Greenspan and right-wing economists were right on point. None of this 
is to say that there aren't valid criticisms of the Clinton administration. 
It's just that we should not look back in hindsight and judge Bill 
Clinton's administration by today's standards. He did a good job, 
considering the time and situation. 

Here's the problem though with voting for Hillary today; she does not seem 
to understand that it is not 1992. Today, we should all be able to look 
back and see our mistakes. We should see that as necessary as raising 
corporate money was in '92, it's become an impediment to any kind of 
functioning democracy. Our congress people spend 30 hours of their week 
raising funds, and those funds come, always, with strings attached. I want 
Hillary to repudiate this before I will vote for her. I want her to look 
back at campaign finance, and the harm caused by conservative economics, 
and the half-measure social policies and recognize that we don't need more 
of that. 

I'm sure that it is hard for Clinton to turn her back on our current 
political system. She is very good at fundraising, and this has served her 
well. The maddening thing is though, that she is tremendously capable and 
*could* actually change things dramatically. Until I get the clear 
impression that she can see what wrong though, and wants to change it, I 
won't vote for her.

I understand how bad it could get in four years under a Republican 
administration. I'm lucky in that it won't effect me directly the way that 
it will many. Being a white, straight male, I'm not going to be impacted by 
the rollback of abortion rights. I can and do pee wherever I damned-well 
please. No one is going to throw me in jail for my sexual behavior. I have 
an insulation of innate privilege between me and (*truly*) regressive 
likely policies of the right. It's knowing how horrible the world that the 
Republicans want to create that give such pause to the idea of 
half-measures against them, of collusion. A President Hillary Clinton will 
do a very good job of keeping the country afloat, of staying the course, 
and keeping us from sinking, but I'm afraid that if we don't do more than 
this, that it just won't matter. We don't need someone who can bail water 
while the Republicans punch holes in the hull. We've been going in the 
wrong direction for 35 years and need to turn the boat around.

My personal opinion on Hillarys likely VP choice is that she will choose 
someone who is perceived to be liberal, but who isn't known well and who 
doesn't have an established base of supporters. She'll choose someone who 
is a token, and who can be pushed out front to sell odious policies like 
the TPP to the American left. It's early, though, so who knows. If she 
convinced Warren to run with her, I *would* support that ticket, because I 
trust Warren. Warren's policy positions with Hillarys political acumen 
would likely be history changing. Warren would be a repudiation of the past 
35 years" politics as usual, though.﻿
